{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778260914,"nonce":"M82Cs1TwzdX+cvt+N1pjtBQSA3Y=","title":"Constrained-RNN regulator: force u_t = K_RNN(h_t)·x_t, no u_ff channel","message":"Stage 9 in the proposed regulator-coupling / decoupling-chain programme (exploration, not committed). Depends on decoupling decomposition (8fcb6c7) to know whether forcing the constraint is meaningful.\n\n**Question.** If we architecturally prevent the RNN from using an additive feedforward channel, do we recover Δv \u003e 0? This is the hardest test of Gemini's decoupling mechanism: if the regulator-coupling story is right, a structurally constrained RNN should be forced to inflate velocity.\n\n**Two experiments.**\n1. **Constrained-GRU regulator.** Parameterise the policy as u_t = K_RNN(h_t) · x_t: a state-only linear functional, but with time-varying gain emitted by the recurrence. No additive u_ff channel. The hidden state h_t can still carry temporal context (time-into-trial, trajectory history) but cannot emit a target-trajectory drive directly.\n2. **Auxiliary-loss tracker suppression.** Train a standard GRU with an additional loss term penalising ||u_ff||_2 — explicitly punishing the feedforward component. This is a softer version of experiment 1.\n\n**Analytical prediction.** If Gemini's mechanism is correct, both experiments should recover Δv \u003e 0. If neither does, decoupling is not operative even when structurally prevented — the issue lies in the cost schedule, adversary mismatch, or exploration deficit.\n\n**Pathological outcome to watch for.** If experiment 1 recovers Δv \u003e 0 but with grossly degraded task loss, the constraint just breaks training rather than revealing the mechanism — decoupling would then be a *necessary* trade-off, not a choice.\n\n**Cross-refs.** Plan §3 stage 9. Decoupling decomposition 8fcb6c7. Linear baselines d448c9d. Training-methods coord c99ad9d.","files":null}]}